abstract: A. friend has just shown us a handful of beautiful-looking wheat heads, which, upon examination, proves to be filled with the weevil. abstract: GEORGE C. CHURCHWOOD and WM. SEARLS had a fracas here on Monday night. CHURCHWOOD fired three barrels of a revolver at SEARLS, each taking effect. The latter then drew a knife and rushed on CHURCHWOOD, inflicting on him four ghastly wounds, from the effects of which he died on the spot. SEARLS, it is thought, is so seriously wounded that he cannot recover.

abstract: DEAR SIR: I've been lingering around among the roses, this evening, until my heart has got the better of my head. abstract: On Tuesday, three rowdies, (whose names we were unable to obtain,) went into the porter-house of Mrs. HANAGAN, corner of Union avenue and North Second-street, and after drinking, assaulted the landlady, and broke whatever glass that came within their reach. Officer RADDIGAN, of the Second Ward, was called in to restore peace, but no sooner had he opened the door, than he was knocked down and severely beaten by the villians.

abstract: CANARSIE RIOTERS.--Seven of the Canarsie rioters were arraigned on eleven indictments for assault and battery, on two for robbery, and one for riot and tumult, to which they severally pleaded not guilty. Their names are George Higgins, Patrick Costello, Thomas Coggins, John Farrell, Henry Collins, Michael Tally alias Michael Tully, Jacob Siper alias Jacob Seip, and Nathan Swizer alias Nathan Sweitzer.

abstract: CASTLE GARDEN.--"La Favorita" attracted a moderate audience last evening. We are disposed to think that many of the "regulars" postponed their attendance in view of the attraction for to-morrow night. "Don Giovanni" is undoubtedly a greater favorite with the musical public than "La Favorita," notwithstanding its portentous name.

abstract: FOUND DROWNED.--The body of a German, apparently about fifty years of age, was found floating in Newtown Creek, near the Maspeth road, on Wednesday evening. Deceased was very respectably dressed, having on a black broadcloth coat, black pants, old-fashioned blue vest, new fine boots, and a German linen shirt, with a false bosom; on the bottom of the shirt were the initials "L. W." A yellow cloth handkerchief was found in his coat pocket.

abstract: TOMB OF BENJAMIN FRANKLIN.--Under this caption, we lately published a paragraph calling attention to a well-founded complaint made by the New-York Evangelist, of the obscure and inaccessible position which the grave of the great FRANKLIN now occupies. We find that it has attracted more general attention in all directions than we had expected, and it has afforded us much gratification to notice the unanimity with which the newspaper press has taken up the subject.

abstract: RHENISH-BELGIAN GALLERY.--A collection of paintings, by living German and Belgian artists, was opened yesterday at 663 Broadway. The pictures are exhibited in the rooms of the National Academy of Design, and make but a poor show. The advertisement informs us that it is" the largest collection of modern paintings ever exhibited in America."

abstract: The statement of the defalcation of WM. C. ZANTZINGER, late Disbursing Agent of the State Department, undoubtedly has its origin in malice. His accounts had not yet been settled, illness having prevented his making them up. The difficulty yesterday would all have been avoided had the Department given him notice that his check for $10,000 had not been honored.

abstract: The one hundred and fifty-third commencement of Yale College marks an important epoch in its history. The resignation of Professor SILLIMAN, who for over half a century has been one of her most valuable professors, will be deeply felt by the institution; and long will it be ere the place left vacant will be filled by one as well fitted to perform the numerous and arduous duties pertaining to it.
